8 SECTION 4.(a) G.S. 20-16.3 reads as rewritten:
9 "§ 20-16.3. Alcohol and drug screening tests required of certain drivers; approval of test
10 devices and manner of use by Department of Health and Human Services; use
11 of test results or refusal.
12 (a) When Alcohol or Drug Screening Test May Be Required; Not an Arrest. – A
13 law-enforcement officer may require the driver of a vehicle to submit to an alcohol screening test
14 within a relevant time after the driving test, drug screening test, or an alcohol screening test and
15 a drug screening test, if the officer has:has either of the following:
16 (1) Reasonable grounds to believe that the driver has consumed alcohol alcohol,
17 an impairing substance other than alcohol, or alcohol and an impairing
18 substance other than alcohol, and has:has done either of the following:
19 a. Committed a moving traffic violation; orviolation.
20 b. Been involved in an accident or collision; orcollision.
21 (2) An articulable and reasonable suspicion that the driver has committed an
22 implied-consent offense under G.S. 20-16.2, and the driver has been lawfully
23 stopped for a driver's license check or otherwise lawfully stopped or lawfully
24 encountered by the officer in the course of the performance of the officer's
25 duties.
26 Requiring a driver to submit to an alcohol screening a test in accordance with this section does
27 not in itself constitute an arrest.
28 (b) Approval of Alcohol Screening Devices and Manner of Use. – The Department of
29 Health and Human Services is directed to examine and approve devices suitable for use by
30 law-enforcement officers in making on-the-scene tests of drivers for alcohol concentration. For
31 each alcohol screening device or class of devices approved, the Department must adopt
32 regulations governing the manner of use of the device. For any alcohol screening device that tests
33 the breath of a driver, the Department is directed to specify in its regulations the shortest feasible
34 minimum waiting period that does not produce an unacceptably high number of false positive
35 test results.
36 (b1) Approval of Oral Drug Screening Devices and Manner of Use. – The Department of
37 Health and Human Services is directed to examine and approve oral fluid drug screening devices
38 suitable for use by law-enforcement officers to test drivers for the presence of impairing
39 substances other than alcohol in oral fluids. For each device or class of devices approved, the
40 Department must adopt regulations governing the manner of use of the device and the level of
41 training required for officers who are authorized to use the device. The Department is directed to
42 specify in its regulations the shortest feasible minimum waiting period that does not produce an
43 unacceptably high number of false positive test results.
44 (c) Tests Must Be Made with Approved Devices and in Approved Manner. – No
45 screening test for alcohol concentration is a valid one under this section unless the device used is
46 one approved by the Department and the screening test is conducted in accordance with the
47 applicable regulations of the Department as to the manner of its use.
48 (d) Use of Screening Test Results or Refusal by Officer. – The fact that a driver showed
49 a positive or negative result on an alcohol screening test, but not the actual alcohol concentration
50 result, result of an alcohol screening test, the type of impaired substance present as shown by an
51 oral fluid drug screening test, or a driver's refusal to submit to a test may be used by a
