13 impairing substances other than alcohol and had in his or her body one or more
14 previously consumed impairing substances other than alcohol."
15 SECTION 4.(b) G.S. 20-138.7(d) reads as rewritten:
16 "(d) Alcohol Screening Test. – Notwithstanding any other provision of law, an alcohol
17 screening test may be administered to a driver suspected of violating subsection (a) of this
18 section, and the results of an alcohol screening test or the driver's refusal to submit may be used
19 by a law enforcement officer, a court, or an administrative agency in determining if alcohol was
20 present in the driver's body. No alcohol screening tests are valid under this section unless the
21 device used is one approved by the Commission for Public Health, Department of Health and
22 Human Services, and the screening test is conducted in accordance with the applicable
23 regulations of the Commission Department of Health and Human Services as to the manner of
24 its use."
25 SECTION 4.(c) G.S. 15A-534.2(d)(2) reads as rewritten:
26 "(2) For any purpose in any proceeding if the test was not performed by a method
27 approved by the Commission for Public Health Department of Health and
28 Human Services under G.S. 20-139.1 and by a person licensed to administer
29 the test by the Department of Health and Human Services."
30 SECTION 4.(d) This section becomes effective December 1, 2025, and applies to
31 offenses committed on or after that date.
32
33 PROVISIONS RELATED TO TRANSPARENCY IN COURT PROCEEDINGS
34 INVOLVING IMPAIRED DRIVERS
35 SECTION 5.(a) G.S. 7A-191.1 reads as rewritten:
36 "§ 7A-191.1. Recording of proceeding in which defendant pleads guilty or no contest to
37 felony in district court.
38 (a) The trial judge shall require that a true, complete, and accurate record be made of the
39 proceeding in which a defendant pleads guilty or no contest to a Class H or I felony pursuant to
40 G.S. 7A-272.(i) any hearing on an infraction conducted pursuant to Article 66 of Chapter 15A of
41 the General Statutes and (ii) any criminal trial proceeding, including pretrial motions, pleas, plea
42 bargains, an explanation required under G.S. 20-138.4, taking of evidence, sentencing hearings,
43 posttrial motions, and requests for limited driving privileges. A proceeding described in this
44 subsection shall be recorded, both video and audio, using electronic or other mechanical devices
45 provided by the Administrative Office of the Courts.
46 (b) It is the duty of the clerk of superior court, or another person designated by the clerk,
47 to (i) operate the recording device described in subsection (a) of this section and (ii) preserve any
48 recording produced by the device. Notwithstanding any provision of law to the contrary, making
49 a recording produced in accordance with this section available online in a format that allows a
50 person to view the recording and download or save the recording to his or her device is allowed
51 and sufficient to comply with any provision of Chapter 132 of the General Statutes requiring
DRH10048-MLf-23 Page 9

General Assembly Of North Carolina Session 2025
1 access to public records. A proceeding described in subsection (a) of this section may be deleted
2 in accordance with a retention schedule adopted and implemented by the Administrative Office
3 of the Courts."
4 SECTION 5.(b) G.S. 7A-109.2 reads as rewritten:
5 "§ 7A-109.2. Records of dispositions in criminal cases; impaired driving integrated data
6 system.
7 (a) Each clerk of superior court shall ensure that all records of dispositions in criminal
8 cases, including those records filed electronically, contain all the essential information about the
9 case, including the the name of the presiding judge and the attorneys representing the State and
10 the defendant.
11 (b) In addition to the information required by subsection (a) of this section for all offenses
12 involving impaired driving as defined by G.S. 20-4.01, all charges of driving while license
13 revoked for an impaired driving license revocation as defined by G.S. 20-28.2, and any other
14 violation of the motor vehicle code involving the operation of a vehicle and the possession,
15 consumption, use, or transportation of alcoholic beverages, the clerk shall include in the
16 electronic records the following information:
17 (1) The reasons for any pretrial dismissal by the court.
18 (2) The alcohol concentration reported by the charging officer or chemical
19 analyst, if any.
20 (3) The reasons for any suppression of evidence.
21 (4) The disposition of the charge.
22 (c) In addition to the information required under subsections (a) and (b) of this section,
23 for defendants sentenced pursuant to G.S. 20-179, the clerk shall include in the electronic records
24 (i) each grossly aggravating factor, aggravating factor, and mitigating factor found by the court
25 and (ii) the level of punishment imposed by the court.
26 (d) The Administrative Office of the Courts shall publish an annual report no later than
27 September 1 of each year on its website that includes the information required by this section for
28 the fiscal year immediately preceding the date of the report. The report shall include statewide
29 and countywide summaries of the number of charges, dispositions, sentencing factors, and
30 sentencing levels. Additionally, for each county, the report shall include each type of charge filed
31 and all of the information required by this section for each charge."
32 SECTION 5.(c) Section 33 of S.L. 2006-253, as amended by Section 5 of S.L.
33 2007-493, reads as rewritten:
34 "SECTION 33. Section 6 becomes effective August 21, 2006, and applies to hearings held
35 on or after that date. Sections 20.1, 20.2, and the requirement that the Administrative Office of
36 the Courts electronically record certain data contained in subsection (c) of G.S. 20-138.4, as
37 amended by Section 19 of this act, become effective after the next rewrite of the superior court
38 clerks system by the Administrative Office of the Courts. December 1, 2025. Section 22.4
39 becomes effective December 1, 2006. The remainder of this act becomes effective December 1,
40 2006, and applies to offenses committed on or after that date."
41 SECTION 5.(d) The first report required under G.S. 7A-109.2(d), as enacted by
42 subsection (b) of this section, shall include information from December 1, 2025, through June
43 30, 2026, and shall be published no later than September 1, 2026.
44 SECTION 5.(e) Subsections (a) and (b) of this section become effective December
45 1, 2025, and apply to any hearing, trial, or disposition of charges occurring on or after that date.
46 The remainder of this section is effective when it becomes law.
47
48 PROVISIONS RELATED TO ALLOWING REPEAT OFFENDERS A METHOD TO
49 PROVE THEIR SOBRIETY AND OBTAIN A LEGAL METHOD TO OPERATE A
50 VEHICLE
51 SECTION 6.(a) G.S. 20-19 is amended by adding a new subsection to read:
Page 10 DRH10048-MLf-23

General Assembly Of North Carolina Session 2025
1 "(d1) Notwithstanding any other provision of law, when a person's license is revoked for
2 an impaired driving offense and the person is sentenced pursuant to G.S. 20-179, the Division
3 may conditionally restore the person's license after it has been revoked for at least one year if the
4 person (i) provides the Division with a certificate of graduation from a Drug Treatment or Driving
5 While Impaired (DWI) Treatment Court Program established pursuant to Article 62 of Chapter
6 7A of the General Statutes, (ii) successfully completes a Division-approved driver improvement
7 clinic described in G.S. 20-16, and (iii) pays, in addition to any other applicable fees, a fee of
8 twenty-five dollars ($25.00). The twenty-five dollar ($25.00) fee shall be deposited in the
9 Highway Fund. If the Division restores the person's license, it shall place all of the following
10 restrictions, requirements, and conditions on the person for the duration of the original revocation
11 period:
12 (1) A requirement that all registered vehicles owned by that person be equipped
13 with a functioning ignition interlock system in accordance with
14 G.S. 20-17.8(c1).
15 (2) A restriction that the person may operate only a motor vehicle equipped with
16 a functioning ignition interlock system of a type approved by the
17 Commissioner that is set to prohibit driving with an alcohol concentration of
18 greater than 0.02.
19 (3) A requirement that the person personally activate the ignition interlock system
20 before driving the motor vehicle.
21 In lieu of an ignition interlock system, the Division may impose a requirement that the person
22 prove abstention from the consumption of alcohol by use of a continuous alcohol monitoring
23 system approved under G.S. 15A-1343.3. The provider of the continuous alcohol monitoring
24 system shall send reports prepared in accordance with this subsection to the Division.
25 In addition, the Division may place other reasonable restrictions, requirements, and
26 conditions on the person for the duration of the original revocation period."
27 SECTION 6.(b) This section becomes effective December 1, 2025.
28
29 REVISION RELATED TO THE OFFENSE OF AIDING OR ABETTING THE SALE TO
30 OR PURCHASE BY UNDERAGE PERSONS OF ALCOHOLIC BEVERAGES
31 SECTION 7.(a) G.S. 18B-302(c)(2) reads as rewritten:
32 "(2) By Person over Lawful Age. – Any Except as otherwise provided in this
33 subdivision, any person who is over the lawful age to purchase and who aids
34 or abets another in violation of subsection (a), (a1), or (b) of this section is
35 guilty of a Class 1 misdemeanor. Any person who is over the lawful age to
36 purchase and who aids or abets a person under the lawful age to purchase in
37 violation of subsection (a), (a1), or (b) of this section is guilty of a Class F
38 felony if the person under the lawful age to purchase consumed the alcoholic
39 beverage involved in the violation and serious bodily injury to the person
40 under lawful age or another results that was proximately caused by the
41 consumption of the alcoholic beverage. For purposes of this subdivision, the
42 term "serious bodily injury" is as defined in G.S. 14-32.4."
43 SECTION 7.(b) G.S. 18B-302.1(b) reads as rewritten:
44 "(b) A violation of G.S. 18B-302(c)(2) is either a Class 1 misdemeanor. misdemeanor or
45 a Class F felony. Notwithstanding the provisions of G.S. 15A-1340.23, if the court imposes a
46 sentence that does not include an active punishment, the court must include among the conditions
47 of probation a requirement that the person pay a fine of at least five hundred dollars ($500.00) as
48 authorized by G.S. 15A-1343(b)(9) and a requirement that the person complete at least 25 hours
49 of community service, as authorized by G.S. 15A-1343(b1)(6). If the person has a previous
50 conviction of this offense in the four years immediately preceding the date of the current offense,
51 and the court imposes a sentence that does not include an active punishment, the court must
DRH10048-MLf-23 Page 11

General Assembly Of North Carolina Session 2025
1 include among the conditions of probation a requirement that the person pay a fine of at least one
2 thousand dollars ($1,000) as authorized by G.S. 15A-1343(b)(9) and a requirement that the
3 person complete at least 150 hours of community service, as authorized by
4 G.S. 15A-1343(b1)(6)."
5 SECTION 7.(c) This section becomes effective December 1, 2025, and applies to
6 offenses committed on or after that date.
7
8 SEVERABILITY CLAUSE, CRIMINAL SAVINGS CLAUSE, AND EFFECTIVE DATE
9 SECTION 8.(a) If any provision of this act or its application is held invalid, the
10 invalidity does not affect other provisions or applications of this act that can be given effect
11 without the invalid provisions or application and, to this end, the provisions of this act are
12 severable.
13 SECTION 8.(b) Prosecutions for offenses committed before the effective date of
14 this act are not abated or affected by this act, and the statutes that would be applicable but for
15 this act remain applicable to those prosecutions.
16 SECTION 8.(c) Except as otherwise provided in this act, this act is effective when
17 it becomes law.
